QUESTION 1

Part A

yelp_business <- read.csv("yelp_business.csv")
yelp_business_subset <- yelp_business %>% subset(city=="Las Vegas")

Part B

median(yelp_business_subset$longitude)
## [1] -115.1912
median(yelp_business_subset$latitude)
## [1] 36.12651

Part C

yelp_business_subset %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles("Esri") %>%
  addCircles(~longitude,~latitude,
             weight = 1,color = "red") %>%
  setView(lat = median(yelp_business_subset$latitude),
          lng = median(yelp_business_subset$longitude),
          zoom = 10)

Part D

yelp_business_subset %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles("Esri") %>%
  addCircles(~longitude,~latitude,
             weight = 1,
             radius = sqrt(yelp_business_subset$review_count),
             color = "gray") %>%
  setView(lat = median(yelp_business_subset$latitude),
          lng = median(yelp_business_subset$longitude),
          zoom = 10)

Part E

This histogram is left skewed. Most of restaurants have stars between 3 and 4. Since it is left skewed the median of stars is bigger than their mean.

ggplot(yelp_business, aes(x=stars)) + geom_histogram(color="dark green", fill="grey",bins = 30) +
  labs(title="Histogram of Stars")

Part F

Most of the observations are in the first column which review count is zero.The histogram is right skewed.There is no observations bigger than 2000.

ggplot(yelp_business, aes(x=review_count)) + geom_histogram(color="dark blue", fill="blue",bins = 20)

Part G

new_data <- head(yelp_business[order(yelp_business$review_count,decreasing = TRUE),],100)

new_data %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles("Esri") %>%
  addMarkers(~longitude, ~latitude,
             popup = paste0(
               "<b> Name of Restaurants: </b>", 
               new_data$name)) %>%
  setView(lng = median(new_data$longitude),
          lat = median(new_data$latitude),
          zoom = 10)

QUESTION 2

Part A

TitanicData_First10 <- sqldf("SELECT * FROM titanic3 LIMIT 100")

Part B

TitanicSubset2Cols <- sqldf("SELECT pclass,survived FROM titanic3")

Part C

sqldf("SELECT COUNT(sex) AS number_of_female FROM titanic3 
      WHERE sex=='female'")
##   number_of_female
## 1              466

Part D

sqldf("SELECT COUNT(sex) AS female_southampton
      FROM titanic3 
      WHERE sex=='female' AND embarked=='Southampton'")
##   female_southampton
## 1                291

Part E

sqldf("SELECT SUM(fare) AS sumofprice_bygender,sex
      FROM titanic3 GROUP BY sex")
##   sumofprice_bygender    sex
## 1            21528.31 female
## 2            22022.17   male

Part F

sqldf("SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT cabin) AS number_of_cabins
      FROM titanic3")
##   number_of_cabins
## 1              187

Part G

sqldf("SELECT COUNT(name) AS name_start_with_A
      FROM titanic3 WHERE name LIKE 'A%'")
##   name_start_with_A
## 1                75

Part H

sqldf("SELECT COUNT(*)-COUNT(body) AS na_values
      FROM titanic3")
##   na_values
## 1      1188

Part I

sqldf("SELECT pclass,
      AVG(CASE WHEN survived = '1' THEN 1.0 ELSE 0 END) as survival_rate
      FROM titanic3
      GROUP BY pclass")
##   pclass survival_rate
## 1    1st     0.6191950
## 2    2nd     0.4296029
## 3    3rd     0.2552891

Part J

sqldf("SELECT sex,AVG(age) AS average_age_bygender
      FROM titanic3
      WHERE survived=='1' GROUP BY sex")
##      sex average_age_bygender
## 1 female             29.81535
## 2   male             26.97778
